article.headline: USC 84, Oregon 78
article.story: EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- There was no need for last second heroics for USC this time out. Gabe Pruitt made sure of that. One game after needing a buzzer-beating shot from Nick Young to beat Oregon State, the Trojans got 30 points from Pruitt in an 84-78 win against Oregon Saturday at McArthur Court, as USC swept the Oregon road trip for the first time since 1997. Pruitt made 8-of-12 shots from the field and was 6-of-8 from the 3-point line, one off his career high. He also was 8 of 12 from the free-throw line. "It always feels good to get one on the road," said Pruitt, a sophomore forward. "It feels good. I had a good game. It was one of those nights. I was feeling it." Four other players scored in double figures for the Trojans (14-6 overall, 5-4 Pac-10), as Young had 16 points, Lodrick Stewart scored 14, Ryan Francis 11 and N'diaye Abdoulaye 10. Southern Cal shot 53 percent from the field overall and made 10 3-pointers. "Our guys really played unselfishly tonight," USC coach Tim Floyd said. "A lot of our baskets came from the extra pass." Reserve guards Chamberlain Oguchi and Bryce Taylor led the Ducks (10-11, 4-5) with 25 and 18 points, respectively. It was a career-high for Oguchi, who made 6-of-9 3-pointers and 8-of-11 shots overall. Taylor made seven of his 11 field-goal attempts. "We didn't expect Gabe to get off the way he did," Taylor admitted. "But we also didn't defend like we knew we had to." Led by Pruitt's 15 points and three 3-pointers, the Trojans went into halftime up 39-32 and shooting 64 percent from the field. Down 25-24, Pruitt hit two free throws at the 5:20 mark to put the Trojans up 26-25, then followed with back-to-back 3-pointers as USC went on a 12-3 run to take a 38-28 lead with 1:06 left in the half. The Trojans went up 55-45 at the 11:31 mark of the second half on free throws by Lodrick Stewart, but the Ducks responded with a 19-8 run to take their first lead of the second half, 64-63, with 6:24 to play. Taylor and Oguchi each hit a pair of 3-pointers during that run. Southern Cal quickly tied it back up on a free throw by Abdoulaye, and a dunk by Nick Young at the 5:37 mark put the Trojans back up for good, 66-64. "They have some really good players on their team that are known for knocking down big shots and we just gave them too many open opportunities," Oguchi said. The Ducks were hampered in the final minutes after losing starting point guard Aaron Brooks and his primary backup, Brandon Lincoln to fouls with a minute of each other with under four minutes to play. "I've never had a situation where both of my point guards fouled out," Oregon coach Ernie Kent said. "The game just got away from us defensively. We played well enough offensively to get the win." Oregon shot 53 percent from the field, but it also made only 12 of 23 free throws.
